Subject:    <a href="?t=95837890700014&r=1&w=2">Nameservers with incomplete information about a zone</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837785800032&r=1&w=2">Bruce Orchard &lt;Bruce.Orchard () scarecrow ! waisman ! wisc ! edu&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198812">1988-12-30 3:18:37</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783027045&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837783027045&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I have seen cases where a domain name server that was pointed to by an
NS resource record does not have the full information about the zone.
I think this is not allowed by RFC's 1034 and 1035.  They say that an
NS resource record points to an authoritative server for a zone and
that an authoritative server has complete information about the zone.

That a server does not have complete information about a zone can be
seen by doing a request to the server with no recursion requested.
Then the server will respond to queries for which the information is
not in its cache with a referral to a list of servers.  The list of
servers may include the server itself.

Bruce Orchard
University of Wisconsin-Madison

